A Cut-free Sequent Calculus for
Bi-Intuitionistic Logic:
Extended Version

Linda Buisman    Rajeev Goré
Abstract

Bi-intuitionistic logic is the extension of intuitionistic logic with a connective dual to implication. Bi-intuitionistic logic was introduced by Rauszer as a Hilbert calculus with algebraic and Kripke semantics. But her subsequent “cut-free” sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} has recently been shown by Uustalu to fail cut-elimination. We present a new cut-free sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}, and prove it sound and complete with respect to its Kripke semantics. Ensuring completeness is complicated by the interaction between implication and its dual, similarly to future and past modalities in tense logic. Our calculus handles this interaction using extended sequents which pass information from premises to conclusions using variables instantiated at the leaves of failed derivation trees. Our simple termination argument allows our calculus to be used for automated deduction, although this is not its main purpose.

1 Introduction

Propositional intuitionistic logic (𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}) has connectives →→\rightarrow, ∧\wedge, ∨\vee and ¬\neg, with ¬φ𝜑\neg\varphi often defined as ¬φ:=φ→⟂assign𝜑𝜑→perpendicular-to\neg\varphi:=\varphi\rightarrow\perp. 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} has a well-known Kripke semantics, where a possible world w𝑤w makes φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi true if every successor v𝑣v that makes φ𝜑\varphi true also makes ψ𝜓\psi true. 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} also has an algebraic semantics in terms of Heyting algebras, and there is a well-known embedding from 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} into the classical modal logic 𝚂𝟺𝚂𝟺\mathtt{S4}. 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} is constructive in that it rejects the Law of Excluded Middle: that is, φ∨¬φ𝜑𝜑\varphi\vee\neg\varphi is not a theorem of 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}.

Propositional dual intuitionistic logic (𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt}) has connectives   , ∧\wedge, ∨\vee and ∼similar-to\sim\ , with ∼φsimilar-toabsent𝜑\sim\varphi often defined as ∼φ:=⊤​φsimilar-toabsent𝜑assigntop𝜑\sim\varphi:=\top\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;\varphi. 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} also has Kripke semantics, where a possible world w𝑤w makes φ​​ψ𝜑𝜓\varphi\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;\psi true if there exists a predecessor v𝑣v where φ𝜑\varphi holds, but ψ𝜓\psi does not hold: that is, φ𝜑\varphi excludes ψ𝜓\psi. Thus, the    connective of 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} is dual to implication in 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}. 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} also has algebraic semantics in terms of Brouwer algebras [13]. There is a less well-known embedding from 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} into 𝚂𝟺𝚂𝟺\mathtt{S4}. 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} is para-consistent in that it rejects the Law of Non-contradiction: that is, φ∧∼φsimilar-tolimit-from𝜑𝜑\varphi\wedge\sim\varphi is 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt}-satisfiable. Various names have been used for   : coimplication [24, 23], subtraction [2, 3], pseudo-difference [16], explication [15]. We refer to it as exclusion.

Bi-intuitionistic logic (𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}), also known as subtractive logic and Heyting-Brouwer logic, is the union of 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} and 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt}, and it is a conservative extension of both. 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} was first studied by Rauszer [15, 16]. 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} is an interesting logic to study, since it combines the constructive aspects of 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} with the para-consistency of 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt}. While every 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}-theorem is also a 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}-theorem, adding 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} connectives introduces a non-constructive aspect to the logic – the disjunction property does not hold for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae if they contain   . Note that 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} differs from intuitionistic logic with constructive negation, also known as constructible falsity [14], where the disjunction property does hold.

While the proof theory of 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} and 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} separately has been studied extensively and there are many cut-free sequent systems for 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} (for example, [8, 6, 5]) and 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} (for example, [20, 4]), the case for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} is less satisfactory. Although Rauszer presented a sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} in [15] and “proved” it cut-free, Uustalu has recently given a counter-example [21] to her cut-elimination theorem: the formula p→(q∨(r→((pq)∧r))p\rightarrow(q\vee(r\rightarrow((p\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;q)\wedge r)) is 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}-valid, but cannot be derived in Rauszer’s calculus without the cut rule. Similarly, Uustalu’s counterexample shows that Crolard’s sequent calculus [2] for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} is not cut-free. Uustalu’s counterexample fails in both Rauszer’s and Crolard’s calculi because they limit certain sequent rules to singleton succedents or antecedents in the conclusion, and the rules do not capture the interaction between implication and exclusion.

Uustalu and Pinto have also given a cut-free sequent-calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} in [23]. Since only the abstract of this work has been published so far, we have not been able to examine their sequent rules, or verify their proofs. According to the abstract [23] and personal communication with Uustalu [22], his calculus uses labelled formulae, thereby utilising some semantic aspects, such as explicit worlds and accessibility, directly in the rules. Hence a traditional cut-free sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} is still an open problem.

We present a new purely syntactic cut-free sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}. We avoid Rauszer’s and Crolard’s restrictions on the antecedents and succedents for certain rules by basing our rules on Dragalin’s 𝙶𝙷𝙿𝙲𝙶𝙷𝙿𝙲\mathtt{GHPC} [5] which allows multiple formulae on both sides of sequents. To maintain intuitionistic soundness, we restrict the premise of the implication-right rule to a singleton in the succedent. Dually, the premise of our exclusion-left rule is restricted to a singleton in the antecedent. But using Dragalin’s calculus and its dual does not give us 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} completeness. We therefore follow Schwendimann [17], and use sequents which pass relevant information from premises to conclusions using variables instantiated at the leaves of failed derivation trees. We then recompute parts of our derivation trees using the new information, similarly to the restart technique of [11]. Our calculus thus uses a purely syntactic addition to traditional sequents, rather than resorting to a semantic mechanism such as labels. Our termination argument also relies on two new rules from Śvejdar [18].

If we were interested only in decision procedures, we could obtain a decision procedure for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} by embedding it into the tense logic 𝙺𝚝.𝚂𝟺formulae-sequence𝙺𝚝𝚂𝟺\mathtt{Kt.S4} [24], and using tableaux for description logics with inverse roles [11]. However, an embedding into 𝙺𝚝.𝚂𝟺formulae-sequence𝙺𝚝𝚂𝟺\mathtt{Kt.S4} provides no proof-theoretic insights into 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} itself. Moreover, the restart technique of Horrocks et al. [11] involves non-deterministic expansion of disjunctions, which is complicated by inverse roles. Their actual implementation avoids this non-determinism by keeping a global view of the whole counter-model under construction. In contrast, we handle this non-determinism by syntactically encoding it using variables and extended formulae, neither of which have a semantic content. Our purely syntactic approach is preferable for proof-theoretic reasons, since models are never explicitly involved in the proof system: see Remark 3.

The rest of the paper is organized as follows. In Section 2, we define the syntax and semantics of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}. In Section 3, we introduce our sequent calculus 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} and give an example derivation of Uustalu’s interaction formula. We prove the soundness and completeness of 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} in Sections 4 and 5 respectively. In Section 6, we outline further work.

Lemma 1

The persistence property also holds for formulae, that is:

∀ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩.∀u,w∈𝒲.∀φ∈𝐹𝑚𝑙.(w⊨φ&w​ℛ​u⇒u⊨φ).formulae-sequencefor-allℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑfor-all𝑢𝑤𝒲for-all𝜑𝐹𝑚𝑙⊨𝑤𝜑𝑤ℛ𝑢⇒𝑢⊨𝜑\forall{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle.\forall u,w\in{\cal{W}}.\forall\varphi\in\mathit{Fml}.(w\vDash\varphi\And w{\cal{R}}u\Rightarrow u\vDash\varphi).
Proof

By induction on the length of φ𝜑\varphi.

Lemma 2

The reverse persistence property holds:

∀ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩.∀u,w∈𝒲.∀φ∈𝐹𝑚𝑙.(w⊭φ&u​ℛ​w⇒u⊭φ).formulae-sequencefor-allℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑfor-all𝑢𝑤𝒲for-all𝜑𝐹𝑚𝑙⊭𝑤𝜑𝑢ℛ𝑤⇒𝑢⊭𝜑\forall{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle.\forall u,w\in{\cal{W}}.\forall\varphi\in\mathit{Fml}.(w\nvDash\varphi\And u{\cal{R}}w\Rightarrow u\nvDash\varphi).
Proof

Reverse persistence follows from persistence, because the truth valuation is binary. That is, suppose for a contradiction that

∃ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩,∃u,w∈𝒲.∃φ∈𝐹𝑚𝑙.(w⊭φ&u​ℛ​w&u⊨φ).formulae-sequenceformulae-sequenceℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑ𝑢𝑤𝒲𝜑𝐹𝑚𝑙⊭𝑤𝜑𝑢ℛ𝑤𝑢⊨𝜑\exists{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle,\exists u,w\in{\cal{W}}.\exists\varphi\in\mathit{Fml}.(w\nvDash\varphi\And u{\cal{R}}w\And u\vDash\varphi).

Then u⊨φ⊨𝑢𝜑u\vDash\varphi and u​ℛ​w𝑢ℛ𝑤u{\cal{R}}w together with the persistence property give us w⊨φ⊨𝑤𝜑w\vDash\varphi, which contradicts w⊭φ⊭𝑤𝜑w\nvDash\varphi.

We write ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon to mean the empty set. Given two sets of formulae ΔΔ\Delta and ΓΓ\Gamma, we write Δ,ΓΔΓ\Delta,\Gamma for Δ∪ΓΔΓ\Delta\cup\Gamma. Given a set of formulae ΔΔ\Delta and a formula φ𝜑\varphi, we write Δ,φΔ𝜑\Delta,\varphi for Δ∪{φ}Δ𝜑\Delta\cup\{\varphi\}.

Definition 7

Given a model ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩ℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑ{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle, a world w∈𝒲𝑤𝒲w\in{\cal{W}} and sets of formulae ΓΓ\Gamma and ΔΔ\Delta, we write:

w⊨Γ if ∀φ∈Γ.w⊨φw=|Δ if ∀φ∈Δ.w⊭φ.⊨𝑤Γ if formulae-sequencefor-all𝜑Γ⊨𝑤𝜑italic-=|𝑤Δ if formulae-sequencefor-all𝜑Δ⊭𝑤𝜑\begin{array}[]{lll}w\vDash\Gamma&\text{ if }&\forall\varphi\in\Gamma.w\vDash\varphi\\ w=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta&\text{ if }&\forall\varphi\in\Delta.w\nvDash\varphi.\\ \end{array}

As a corollary, for any world w𝑤w, we vacuously have w⊨ϵ⊨𝑤italic-ϵw\vDash\epsilon and w=|ϵitalic-=|𝑤italic-ϵw=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\epsilon.

Definition 8 (Consequence)

Given two sets ΓΓ\Gamma and ΔΔ\Delta of formulae, Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta means:

∀ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩.∀w∈𝒲. if ​w⊨Γ​ then ​∃φ∈Δ.w⊨φ.formulae-sequencefor-allℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑfor-all𝑤𝒲⊨ if 𝑤Γ then 𝜑Δ⊨𝑤𝜑\forall{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle.\forall w\in{\cal{W}}.\text{ if }w\vDash\Gamma\text{ then }\exists\varphi\in\Delta.w\vDash\varphi.

We write Γ⊮𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptnot-forces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\not\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta to mean that it is not the case that Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta, that is:

∃ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩.∃w∈𝒲.(w⊨Γ&w=|Δ).formulae-sequenceℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑ𝑤𝒲⊨𝑤Γ𝑤italic-=|Δ\exists{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle.\exists w\in{\cal{W}}.(w\vDash\Gamma\And w=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta).

Thus Γ⊮𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptnot-forces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\not\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta means that Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta is falsifiable.

We wish to prove Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta by failing to falsify Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta. By Definition 8, Γ⊮𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptnot-forces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\not\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta means that there exists a 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} model ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩ℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑ{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle that contains a world w0∈𝒲subscript𝑤0𝒲w_{0}\in{\cal{W}} such that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta. We therefore try to construct the model using a standard counter-model construction approach: see [7]. We shall start with an initial world w0subscript𝑤0w_{0} and assume that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta, and then systematically decompose the formulae in ΓΓ\Gamma and ΔΔ\Delta. The procedure will either:

  • •

    lead to a contradiction and therefore conclude that it cannot be the case that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta, therefore Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta holds, OR

  • •

    construct the counter-model successfully and therefore demonstrate that it is possible that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta, therefore Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta does not hold.

3 Our Sequent Calculus 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}

We now present 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}, a Gentzen-style sequent calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}. The sequents have a non-traditional component in the form of variables that are instantiated at the leaves of the derivation tree, and passed back to lower sequents from premises to conclusion. Note that the variables are not names for Kripke models and have no semantic content.

3.1 Sequents

First, we introduce an extended syntax that will help us in the presentation of some of our sequent rules.

Definition 9 (Extended Syntax)

The extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae are defined as follows:

  1. 1.

    If φ𝜑\varphi is a 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formula, then φ𝜑\varphi is an extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formula,

  2. 2.

    If 𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}} and 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} are sets of sets of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae, then ⋁𝒮𝒮\bigvee{\mathcal{S}} and ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} are extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae.

If 𝒮={{φ00,⋯,φ0n},⋯,{φm0,⋯,φmk}}𝒮superscriptsubscript𝜑00⋯superscriptsubscript𝜑0𝑛⋯superscriptsubscript𝜑𝑚0⋯superscriptsubscript𝜑𝑚𝑘{\mathcal{S}}=\{\{\varphi_{0}^{0},\cdots,\varphi_{0}^{n}\},\cdots,\{\varphi_{m}^{0},\cdots,\varphi_{m}^{k}\}\} and

From now on, we implicitly treat extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae as their 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} equivalents. The following semantics follows directly from Definition 9:

We can now extend the definition of forcing and rejecting to extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae in the obvious way. If ΓΓ\Gamma and ΔΔ\Delta are sets of extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae viewed as their 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} equivalents, and φ𝜑\varphi is an extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formula viewed as its 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} equivalent, then:

Definition 11 (Sequent)

A 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} sequent is an expression of the form

𝒮𝒫||Γ⊢Δ\left.\left.\begin{array}[]{l}\genfrac{}{}{0.0pt}{}{{\mathcal{S}}}{{\mathcal{P}}}\end{array}\ \right|\right|\Gamma\vdash\Delta

and consists of the following components:

Left hand side (LHS):

ΓΓ\Gamma, a set of extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae;

Right hand side (RHS):

ΔΔ\Delta, a set of extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae;

𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}}, 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}}, each of which is a set of sets of formulae.

We shall sometimes use Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta to refer to sequents, ignoring the variable values for readability. We shall only do that in cases where the values of the variables are not important to the discussion. Note that the variables do not contain extended 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae.

We now define the meaning of a sequent in terms of the counter-model under construction.

Definition 12 (Falsifiability)

A sequent

𝒮𝒫||Γ⊢Δ\left.\left.\begin{array}[]{l}\genfrac{}{}{0.0pt}{}{{\mathcal{S}}}{{\mathcal{P}}}\end{array}\ \right|\right|\Gamma\vdash\Delta

is falsifiable [at w0subscript𝑤0w_{0} in ℳℳ{\cal{M}}] if and only if there exists a 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} model ℳ=⟨𝒲,ℛ,ϑ⟩ℳ𝒲ℛitalic-ϑ{\cal{M}}=\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}},\vartheta\rangle and ∃w0∈𝒲subscript𝑤0𝒲\exists w_{0}\in{\cal{W}} such that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta.

We say the variable conditions of a sequent

γ=𝒮𝒫||Γ⊢Δ\gamma=\left.\left.\begin{array}[]{l}\genfrac{}{}{0.0pt}{}{{\mathcal{S}}}{{\mathcal{P}}}\end{array}\ \right|\right|\Gamma\vdash\Delta

𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}}-condition:

∃Σ∈𝒮.∀w∈𝒲.w0​ℛ​w⇒w⊨Σformulae-sequenceΣ𝒮for-all𝑤𝒲⇒subscript𝑤0ℛ𝑤𝑤⊨Σ\exists\Sigma\in{\mathcal{S}}.\forall w\in{\cal{W}}.w_{0}{\cal{R}}w\Rightarrow w\vDash\Sigma

Lemma 3

A sequent Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not falsifiable if and only if Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

Proof

Applying the negation of Definition 12 to Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta gives Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

3.2 Sequent Rules

Definition 14 (Sequent Rule)

A sequent rule is of one of the forms

             γ1⋯γn (name)                   γ0 side conditions               γ1⋯γn (name)                    γ0 side conditions               γ1⋯γn (name)                   γ0 side conditions               γ1⋯γn (name)                    γ0 side conditions \begin{array}[]{l}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\leavevmode\lower 24.12498pt\hbox{\vbox{\hbox{\hskip 35.50244pt\hbox{\hskip 4.0pt\hbox{$\gamma_{1}\ \cdots\ \gamma_{n}$}\hskip 4.0pt}}\vskip-2.8pt\nointerlineskip\hbox{\hskip 0.0pt\lower 2.3pt\hbox{{$(name)$}\hskip 3.0pt}\hbox to42.01593pt{\xleaders\hrule\hfill}\lower-0.2pt\hbox{}}\vskip-2.8pt\nointerlineskip\hbox{\hskip 35.50244pt\hbox{\hskip 13.01932pt\hbox{\hbox{\hskip 4.0pt\hbox{$\gamma_{0}$}\hskip 4.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\\ \text{side conditions }\end{array}\ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \ \begin{array}[]{l}\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\ignorespaces\leavevmode\lower 24.12498pt\hbox{\vbox{\hbox{\hskip 35.50244pt\hbox{\hskip 4.0pt\hbox{$\gamma_{1}\ \cdots\ \gamma_{n}$}\hskip 4.0pt}}\vskip-2.8pt\nointerlineskip\hbox{\hskip 0.0pt\lower 2.3pt\hbox{{$(name)$}\hskip 3.0pt}\hbox to42.01593pt{\xleaders\hbox to7.96677pt{\hss\vrule width=3.98337pt,height=0.4pt,depth=0.0pt\hss}\hfill}\lower-0.2pt\hbox{}}\vskip-2.8pt\nointerlineskip\hbox{\hskip 35.50244pt\hbox{\hskip 13.01932pt\hbox{\hbox{\hskip 4.0pt\hbox{$\gamma_{0}$}\hskip 4.0pt}}}}}}\ignorespaces\\ \text{side conditions }\end{array}

where γisubscript𝛾𝑖\gamma_{i}, 0≤i≤n0𝑖𝑛0\leq i\leq n for n≥0𝑛0n\geq 0, are sequents. The rule consists of the following components:

Conclusion:

γ0subscript𝛾0\gamma_{0}, written below the horizontal line;

Premise(s):

Optional, γ1,⋯,γnsubscript𝛾1⋯subscript𝛾𝑛\gamma_{1},\cdots,\gamma_{n}, written above the horizontal line;

Name:

Written to the left of the horizontal line;

Side conditions:

Optional, written underneath the rule;

Branching:

Universal (indicated by a solid line) or existential (indicated by a dashed line); explained shortly.

To achieve completeness and termination for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}, we combine a number of ideas from various existing systems for 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}, as well as use variables for updating worlds with relevant information received from successors and predecessors. Our rules can be divided into two groups: traditional (Fig. 1) and non-traditional (Fig. 2).

Our traditional rules (Fig. 1) are based on Dragalin’s 𝙶𝙷𝙿𝙲𝙶𝙷𝙿𝙲\mathtt{GHPC} [5] for 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} because we require multiple formulae in the succedents and antecedents of sequents for completeness; we have added symmetric rules for the 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} connective   . The main difference is that our (→L)subscript→𝐿(\rightarrow_{L}) rule and the symmetric (R)subscript𝑅(\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{R}) carry their principal formula and all side formulae into the premises. Our rules for ∧\wedge and ∨\vee also carry their principal formula into their premises to assist with termination. Note that there are other approaches to a terminating sequent calculus for 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int}, e.g., Dyckhoff’s contraction-free calculi [6], or history methods by Heuerding et al. [10] and Howe [12]. These methods are less suitable when the interaction between 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} and 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt} formulae needs to be considered, since they erase potentially relevant formulae too soon during backward proof search. Moreover, we found it easier to prove semantic completeness with our loop-checking method than with history-based methods since both [10] and [12] prove completeness using syntactic transformations of derivations. Consequently, while 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} is sound and complete for the 𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{Int} (and 𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙳𝚞𝚊𝚕𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{DualInt}) fragment of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}, it is unlikely to be as efficient on the fragment as these specific calculi.

Our rules for →→\rightarrow on the right and    on the left (Fig. 2) are non-traditional. The (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) and (L)subscript𝐿({\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{L}}) rules have two premises instead of one, and they are connected by existential branching as indicated by the dotted horizontal line. Existential branching means that the conclusion is derivable if some premise is derivable; thus it is dual to the conventional universal branching, where the conclusion is derivable if all premises are derivable. We chose existential branching rather than two separate non-invertible rules so the left premise can communicate information via variables to the right premise. This inter-premise communication and the use of variables is crucial to proving interaction formulae of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}, and it gives our calculus an operational reading.

When applying an existential branching rule during backward proof search, we first create the left premise. If the left premise is non-derivable, then it returns the variables 𝒮1subscript𝒮1{\mathcal{S}}_{1} and 𝒫1subscript𝒫1{\mathcal{P}}_{1}. We then use these variables to create the right premise, which corresponds to the same world as the conclusion, but with updated information. Our existential branching rules work together with (R​e​t)𝑅𝑒𝑡(Ret), which assigns the variables at non-derivable leaves of failed derivation trees, and (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) and (⋁L)subscript𝐿({\bigvee_{L}}), which extract the different variable choices at existential branching rules.

The conclusion of each of our rules assigns the variables based on the variables returned from the premise(s), and we use the indices i,1,2𝑖12i,1,2 to indicate the premise from which the variable takes its value. For rules with a single premise, the variables are simply passed down from premise to conclusion. For example, the conclusion of (∧L)subscript𝐿(\wedge_{L}) in Fig. 1 assigns 𝒮:=𝒮1assign𝒮subscript𝒮1{\mathcal{S}}:={\mathcal{S}}_{1}, where 𝒮1subscript𝒮1{\mathcal{S}}_{1} is the value of the variable at the premise. However, for rules with multiple universally branching premises, we take a union of the sets of sets corresponding to each falsifiable premise. For example, the conclusion of (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) in Fig. 2 assigns 𝒮:=⋃1n𝒮iassign𝒮superscriptsubscript1𝑛subscript𝒮𝑖{\mathcal{S}}:=\bigcup_{1}^{n}{\mathcal{S}}_{i}, where 𝒮isubscript𝒮𝑖{\mathcal{S}}_{i} is the value of the variable at the i𝑖i-th premise.

This way, the sets of sets stored in our variables determinise the return of formulae to lower sequents – each non-derivable premise corresponds to an open branch, and at this point we do not know whether it will stay open once processed in conjunction with lower sequents. Therefore, we need to temporarily keep all open branches: see Example 2. Then the intuition behind adding ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} to the right premise of (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) is that the subsequent application of (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) will create one or more premises, depending on the cardinality of 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}}. Since 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} is a set of sets representing all the open branches, all of the premises of (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) have to be derivable in order to obtain a derivation. On the other hand, if some premises of (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) are non-derivable (open), we form the set that consists of the union of the variables returned by those premises, and pass the union back to lower sequents, and so on. The premises that are derivable contribute only ϵitalic-ϵ\epsilon and are thus ignored by the union operator. Also, we only create the right premise of (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) if every member of 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} introduces new formulae to the current world. Otherwise, the current world already contains one of the open branches, which would still remain open after an application of (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}). To summarise, the sets-of-sets concept of variables is critical to the soundness of 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}, as it allows us to remember the required choices arising further up the tree.

The extended syntax allows us to syntactically encode the variable choices described above. While the variables 𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}} and 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} are sets of sets when we pass them down the tree and combine them using set union, we use ⋁𝒮𝒮\bigvee{\mathcal{S}} on the left and ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} on the right of the sequent to reflect these choices when we add ⋁𝒮𝒮\bigvee{\mathcal{S}} or ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} to the right premise of an existentially branching rule. Then the (⋁L)subscript𝐿({\bigvee_{L}}) and (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) rules break down the extended formulae ⋁𝒮𝒮\bigvee{\mathcal{S}} and ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} to yield several premises, each corresponding to one variable choice. Thus the extended syntax allows us to give an intuitive syntactic representation of the variable choices.

We have also added the rule (→RI)superscriptsubscript→𝑅𝐼({\rightarrow_{R}^{I}}) for implication on the right (and dually, (LI)superscriptsubscript𝐿𝐼({\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{L}^{I}})) originally given by Śvejdar [18]. Rather than immediately creating the successor for a rejected φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi, the (→RI)superscriptsubscript→𝑅𝐼({\rightarrow_{R}^{I}}) rule first pre-emptively adds ψ𝜓\psi to the right hand side of the sequent. Although Śvejdar himself does not give the semantics behind this rule, and is unable to explain the precise role it plays in his calculus, it is very useful in our termination proof. The rule effectively uses the reverse persistence property – if some successor v𝑣v forces φ𝜑\varphi and rejects ψ𝜓\psi, then the current world w𝑤w must reject ψ𝜓\psi too, for if w𝑤w forces ψ𝜓\psi, then by forward persistence so does v𝑣v, thus giving a contradiction.

The side condition on each of our rules is a general blocking condition, where we only explore the premise(s), if they are different from the conclusion. For example, in the (∧R)subscript𝑅(\wedge_{R}) case, the blocking condition means that we apply the rule in backward proof search only if φ∉Δ𝜑Δ\varphi\not\in\Delta and ψ∉Δ𝜓Δ\psi\not\in\Delta, since otherwise some premise would be equal to the conclusion.

𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} also has the subformula property. This is obvious for all rules, except (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) and the dual (L)subscript𝐿({\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{L}}). For these, the right premise “constructs” the formulae ⋀𝒫𝒫\bigwedge{\mathcal{P}} and ⋁𝒮𝒮\bigvee{\mathcal{S}}. However, since 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} and 𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}} are sets of sets of subformulae of the conclusion that are again extracted by (⋀R)subscript𝑅({\bigwedge_{R}}) and (⋁L)subscript𝐿({\bigvee_{L}}), the right premise of (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) and (L)subscript𝐿({\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{L}}) effectively only contains subformulae of the conclusion.

Definition 16

A 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} tree 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}} rooted at γ=𝒫𝒮||Γ⊢Δ\gamma=\left.\left.\begin{array}[]{l}\genfrac{}{}{0.0pt}{}{{\mathcal{P}}}{{\mathcal{S}}}\end{array}\ \right|\right|\Gamma\vdash\Delta is a derivation if:

  1. 1.

    γ𝛾\gamma is the conclusion of a (⟂L)subscriptperpendicular-to𝐿(\perp_{L}), (⊤R)subscripttop𝑅(\top_{R}) or (I​d)𝐼𝑑(Id) rule application, OR,

  2. 2.

    γ𝛾\gamma is the conclusion of a universal branching rule application, and all its premises are derivations, OR,

  3. 3.

    γ𝛾\gamma is the conclusion of an existential branching rule application, and some premise is a derivation.

We say that γ𝛾\gamma is derivable if there exists a derivation for γ𝛾\gamma.

We say that γ𝛾\gamma is not derivable if γ𝛾\gamma has no derivation.

Thus, the open branch corresponding to the bolded member {⊤​q}top𝑞\{\top\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;q\} of 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} remains open. If we did not return both variable choices from the left sibling of (2)2(2), then we might mistakenly derive (2)2(2) without seeing this open branch.

The intuition behind the classification of the logical rules is that the static rules add formulae to the current world in the counter-model, the transitional rules create new worlds and add formulae to them, and the special rules decompose variables returned from non-derivable leaves. We shall prove this formally for each rule later. The classification justifies the following search strategy.

Definition 22 (Degree)

The degree of a 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formula χ𝜒\chi is defined as:

Thus, the degree of φ𝜑\varphi is the number of →→\rightarrow and    connectives in φ𝜑\varphi.

The degree of a sequent Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is defined as:

deg(Γ⊢Δ)=∑φ∈s​f​(Γ∪Δ)deg(φ)deg(\Gamma\vdash\Delta)=\displaystyle{\sum_{\varphi\in sf(\Gamma\cup\Delta)}deg(\varphi)}

Note that we have deliberately defined the degree of a sequent as the sum of the degrees of subformulae, because it allows us to make the following observations, which will be crucial in the main termination proof.

Corollary 1

Since 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} has the subformula property, the degree of a sequent can never increase in backward proof search. In other words, no 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} rule can increase the degree of a sequent.

Corollary 2

Given two sequents γ1subscript𝛾1\gamma_{1} and γ2subscript𝛾2\gamma_{2}, if s​f​(γ2)⊊s​f​(γ1)𝑠𝑓subscript𝛾2𝑠𝑓subscript𝛾1sf(\gamma_{2})\subsetneq sf(\gamma_{1}), then d​e​g​(γ2)<d​e​g​(γ1)𝑑𝑒𝑔subscript𝛾2𝑑𝑒𝑔subscript𝛾1deg(\gamma_{2})<deg(\gamma_{1}). That is, removing some formula φ𝜑\varphi from a sequent during backward proof search decreases the degree of the sequent if φ𝜑\varphi is not a subformula of any other formula in the sequent, since φ𝜑\varphi no longer contributes to the sum of degrees of subformulae.

Theorem 3.1 (Termination)

Every 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}-tree constructed according to the strategy of Definition 18 is finite.

Proof

This can only happen a finite number of times, until no more transitional rules are applicable. Therefore our assumption was wrong, and no branch ℬℬ{\cal{B}} can be infinite. Therefore, every 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}-tree is finite.

4 Soundness

4.1 Proof Outline

Instead of the traditional approach of showing that each rule application preserves validity downwards, we use the notion of falsifiability and show that each rule application preserves falsifiability upwards. We then use Lemma 3 to make the connection between falsifiability and validity.

Also, our addition of variables to the calculus introduces a two-way flow of information in the 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} trees, and this complicates the usually simple soundness proof.

We separate the notion of soundness into two: local soundness, applicable locally to a single rule application, and global soundness, which takes into account the propagation of variables from the leaves down to some node, and possible instances of the operational (R​e​t)𝑅𝑒𝑡(Ret) rule. Note that locality here refers to locality in the 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} trees, not locality in the underlying Kripke models. We use the notions of static and transitional rules to classify the rules according to this latter notion.

4.2 Local soundness

Definition 23 (Local soundness)

A logical rule in 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} is locally sound if and only if:

  • •

    For rules with universal branching: if the conclusion is falsifiable, then some premise is falsifiable;

  • •

    For rules with existential branching: if the conclusion is falsifiable, then all premises are falsifiable.

We shall now show that each static and special rule is locally sound, and we shall then use induction on the height of a derivation tree to extend our proof to arbitrary trees containing static rules, special rules, transitional rules and the operational (R​e​t)𝑅𝑒𝑡(Ret) rule.

Remark 1

Note that the static rules also preserve falsifiability downwards: if some premise π𝜋\pi is falsifiable, then the conclusion γ𝛾\gamma is falsifiable. This is easy to see, since we have L​H​Sπ⊇L​H​Sγ𝐿𝐻subscript𝑆𝛾𝐿𝐻subscript𝑆𝜋LHS_{\pi}\supseteq LHS_{\gamma} and R​H​Sπ⊇R​H​Sγ𝑅𝐻subscript𝑆𝛾𝑅𝐻subscript𝑆𝜋RHS_{\pi}\supseteq RHS_{\gamma}.

4.3 Global soundness

We have shown that all the static and special rules preserve falsifiability upwards, in other words, they are locally sound. Since the 𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}} and 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} variables propagate downwards, from the leaves to the root, we can only reason about the variable conditions of rules when we consider an entire tree rooted at a rule application. Similarly, since the soundness of the transitional rules relies on the variables, we can only reason about it we consider an entire tree rooted at a transitional rule application. We shall now show that 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} rules are globally sound, that is, they preserve falsifiability upwards and variable conditions downwards.

Lemma 9 (Global soundness)

Given any 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} tree 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}}, for every sequent γ0∈𝒯subscript𝛾0𝒯\gamma_{0}\in{{\cal{T}}}, the following holds: if γ0subscript𝛾0\gamma_{0} is falsifiable, then:

  1. 1.

    Some universally branching, or all existentially branching, premises are falsifiable,

  2. 2.

    The variable conditions hold at γ0subscript𝛾0\gamma_{0}.

      Moreover, the variable conditions hold at the right premise, since it also is falsifiable, and of distance ≤kabsent𝑘\leq k from the furthest leaf node of 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}}, so the induction hypothesis applies to it.

4.4 Main Soundness Proof

Lemma 10

If Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is derivable then Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not falsifiable.

Proof

By induction on the height k𝑘k of the derivation.

Base case: For the base case, the height is 1. A derivation of height 1 can only be an instance of (⟂L)subscriptperpendicular-to𝐿(\perp_{L}), (⊤R)subscripttop𝑅(\top_{R}) or (I​d)𝐼𝑑(Id). In each case, γ𝛾\gamma is not falsifiable, as shown in cases 1 to 3 of Lemma 8.

Inductive step: We assume that if there is a derivation for γ𝛾\gamma of height ≤kabsent𝑘\leq k, then γ𝛾\gamma is not falsifiable. We show that if there is a derivation for γ𝛾\gamma of height ≤k+1absent𝑘1\leq k+1, then γ𝛾\gamma is not falsifiable.

For a contradiction, suppose there is a derivation 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}} for γ𝛾\gamma of height k+1𝑘1k+1 and γ𝛾\gamma is falsifiable. Consider the bottom-most rule application ρ𝜌\rho in 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}}, then γ𝛾\gamma is the conclusion of ρ𝜌\rho.

Then, by Definition 16, since 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}} is a derivation, then all universally branching premises, or some existentially branching premise of ρ𝜌\rho are rooted at derivations of height ≤kabsent𝑘\leq k, so by the induction hypothesis, all universally branching premises are, or some existentially branching premise is not falsifiable. But since the conclusion γ𝛾\gamma of ρ𝜌\rho is falsifiable by supposition, then by Lemma 9, some universally branching premise, or all existentially branching premises are falsifiable. Now we have a contradiction, therefore our assumption was wrong and γ𝛾\gamma is not falsifiable.

Theorem 4.1 (Soundness)

If Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is derivable, then Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

Proof

By Lemma 10, we have that Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not falsifiable. Then by Lemma 3, we have Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

5 Completeness

5.1 Proof Outline

We wish to prove:

  • if Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta, then Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is derivable.

Instead, we prove the contrapositive:

  • if Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not derivable, then there exists a counter-model for Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

Our proof is based on a standard technique for proving completeness of tableau calculi: see [9]. We have adapted this technique to a two-sided sequent calculus with variables.

We assume that Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not derivable, meaning that none of the 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}-trees for Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is a derivation. Then we choose formulae from sequents found in possibly different 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}-trees for Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta in order to construct a counter-model for Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta. The counter-model is constructed so that it contains a world w0subscript𝑤0w_{0} such that w0⊨Γ⊨subscript𝑤0Γw_{0}\vDash\Gamma and w0=|Δitalic-=|subscript𝑤0Δw_{0}=\joinrel\mathrel{|}\Delta, hence Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta does not hold.

Definition 24

Given a sequent Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta, we say that:

The following corollaries follow directly from the definition of consistent sequents.

Corollary 3

If Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is consistent, then none of the rules (I​d)𝐼𝑑(Id), (⟂L)subscriptperpendicular-to𝐿(\perp_{L}), (⊤R)subscripttop𝑅(\top_{R}) is applicable to it.

If the sequent

𝒮𝒫||Γ⊢Δ\left.\left.\begin{array}[]{l}\genfrac{}{}{0.0pt}{}{{\mathcal{S}}}{{\mathcal{P}}}\end{array}\ \right|\right|\Gamma\vdash\Delta

Remark 2

As usual, every sequent has a set of one or more “saturations” due to the branching of (∧R)subscript𝑅(\wedge_{R}), (∨L)subscript𝐿(\vee_{L}), etc., rules. The usual approach is to non-deterministically choose one of the non-derivable premises of each such rule. However, in the presence of the inverse relation, a branch that appears open may close once we return variables to a lower sequent. Therefore, we need to temporarily keep all the non-derivable premises, since we do not know which of the open branches will stay open when we return to a lower sequent.

Lemma 11

For each finite non-derivable sequent Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta, there is an effective procedure to construct a finite set ζ={α1,⋯,αn}𝜁subscript𝛼1⋯subscript𝛼𝑛\zeta=\{\alpha_{1},\cdots,\alpha_{n}\} of finite saturated sequents, with Γ∪Δ⊆L​H​S​(αj)∪R​H​S​(αj)⊆s​f​(Γ)∪s​f​(Δ)ΓΔ𝐿𝐻𝑆subscript𝛼𝑗𝑅𝐻𝑆subscript𝛼𝑗𝑠𝑓Γ𝑠𝑓Δ\Gamma\cup\Delta\subseteq LHS(\alpha_{j})\cup RHS(\alpha_{j})\subseteq sf(\Gamma)\cup sf(\Delta) for all 1≤j≤n1𝑗𝑛1\leq j\leq n.

Proof

Since Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is non-derivable, we know from Corollary 4 that Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is consistent. Then from Corollary 3 we know that the (I​d)𝐼𝑑(Id), (⟂L)subscriptperpendicular-to𝐿(\perp_{L}), (⊤R)subscripttop𝑅(\top_{R}) rules are not applicable to Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta. Let 𝒯=Γ⊢Δproves𝒯ΓΔ{{\cal{T}}}=\Gamma\vdash\Delta. While some static rule ρ𝜌\rho is applicable to a leaf of 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}}, extend 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}} by applying ρ𝜌\rho to the leaf to obtain new leaves. Keep the non-derivable leaves only; by Corollary 4 they are consistent. By Theorem 3.1, the saturation process will eventually terminate; let ζ={α1,⋯,αn}𝜁subscript𝛼1⋯subscript𝛼𝑛\zeta=\{\alpha_{1},\cdots,\alpha_{n}\} be the final leaves of 𝒯𝒯{{\cal{T}}}. Since the formulae in each premise are always subformulae of the conclusion, we have that L​H​S​(αj)∪R​H​S​(αj)⊆s​f​(Γ)∪s​f​(Δ)𝐿𝐻𝑆subscript𝛼𝑗𝑅𝐻𝑆subscript𝛼𝑗𝑠𝑓Γ𝑠𝑓ΔLHS(\alpha_{j})\cup RHS(\alpha_{j})\subseteq sf(\Gamma)\cup sf(\Delta) for all 1≤j≤n1𝑗𝑛1\leq j\leq n.

5.4 Main Completeness Proof

We now show how to construct a model graph for Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta from a consistent Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta. Recall from Remark 2 that we need to keep a number of independent versions of worlds because of the choices arising due to disjunctive non-determinism. We do this by storing one or more independent connected-components ⟨𝒲1,ℛ1⟩,⋯,⟨𝒲n,ℛn⟩subscript𝒲1subscriptℛ1⋯subscript𝒲𝑛subscriptℛ𝑛\langle{\cal{W}}_{1},{\cal{R}}_{1}\rangle,\cdots,\langle{\cal{W}}_{n},{\cal{R}}_{n}\rangle in the constructed model graph ⟨𝒲,ℛ⟩𝒲ℛ\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}}\rangle, and the indices (sorts) of worlds and relations tell us the connected-component of the graph to which they belong. We write ⟨𝒲j,ℛj⟩​[j:=i]subscript𝒲𝑗subscriptℛ𝑗delimited-[]assign𝑗𝑖\langle{\cal{W}}_{j},{\cal{R}}_{j}\rangle[j:=i] to relabel the connected component ⟨𝒲j,ℛj⟩subscript𝒲𝑗subscriptℛ𝑗\langle{\cal{W}}_{j},{\cal{R}}_{j}\rangle with sort j𝑗j to a connected component ⟨𝒲i,ℛi⟩subscript𝒲𝑖subscriptℛ𝑖\langle{\cal{W}}_{i},{\cal{R}}_{i}\rangle with sort i𝑖i. Similarly, we also label each member of the variables 𝒫𝒫{\mathcal{P}} and 𝒮𝒮{\mathcal{S}}, so we can later extract the member with sort i𝑖i, corresponding to the component of ⟨𝒲,ℛ⟩𝒲ℛ\langle{\cal{W}},{\cal{R}}\rangle with sort i𝑖i. We write ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbour to mean ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-predecessor or ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-successor.

Our algorithm in Fig. 4 starts by saturating the root world to obtain one or more saturated “states”. For each “state” αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i}, it recursively creates all the ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbours and saturates them, and so on. If during the construction of any ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbour, new information is returned from the higher sequents (Step 2(b)iv), then we delete the entire subtree (connected component of sort i𝑖i) rooted at αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i}, and recreate αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} using the new information (Step 2ivB). This re-creates all the ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbours of αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i}. Otherwise, if none of the ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbours of αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} return any new information, or there are no ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbours for αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i}, then Step 2d instantiates the variables and returns from the recursion. In the latter case, the “state” αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} already has all the required information it can possibly receive from any ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbours, thus αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} is final. Note the duality: new information from a single ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbour means that all of the members of a variable were new, while new information at a “state” αisubscript𝛼𝑖\alpha_{i} means that some ℛℛ{\cal{R}}-neighbour returned new information.

When we return from M​G​C𝑀𝐺𝐶MGC, we form the union of the components of the model graph and the variables from the different “states”, so that the caller of M​G​C𝑀𝐺𝐶MGC can extract the appropriate component at Step 2iiiA.

Remark 3

Note that while the counter-model construction procedure keeps the whole counter-model in memory, this procedure is only used to prove the completeness of 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}. Our procedure for checking the validity of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} formulae (Fig. 3) does not need the whole counter-model, and explores one branch at a time, as is usual for sequent/tableaux calculi.

Theorem 5.1 (Completeness)

𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} is complete: if Γ⊢ΔprovesΓΔ\Gamma\vdash\Delta is not derivable, then there exists a counter-model for Γ⊩𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝Δsubscriptforces𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝ΓΔ\Gamma\Vdash_{{}_{\mathtt{BiInt}}}\Delta.

Definition 26

A di-tree is a directed graph such that if the direction of the edges is ignored, it is a tree.

Theorem 5.2

Every falsifiable 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} sequent can be falsified by a model whose frame is a di-tree, consisting of reflexive points.

Proof

From Lemmas 5 and 6, we know that the construction of new successors for φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi and predecessors for φ​​ψ𝜑𝜓\varphi\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;\psi stops when either there are no rejected φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi-formulae or forced φ​​ψ𝜑𝜓\varphi\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;\psi-formulae in the current world, or the current world already forces φ𝜑\varphi and rejects ψ𝜓\psi. In the latter case, the world itself fulfills the role of the successor or predecessor by reflexivity, and no new successors or predecessors are created.

The reason we are able to avoid proper cycles is the persistence and reverse persistence properties of 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}, used in the (→RI)superscriptsubscript→𝑅𝐼({\rightarrow_{R}^{I}}) and (LI)superscriptsubscript𝐿𝐼({\begin{picture}(10.0,10.0)\put(1.0,0.0){$-$} \put(7.0,0.0){$<$} \end{picture}\;\;_{L}^{I}}) rules.

Consider the →→\rightarrow case. Every time some φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi appears on the RHS of a sequent Γ⊢Δ,φ→ψprovesΓ→Δ𝜑𝜓\Gamma\vdash\Delta,\varphi\rightarrow\psi, we first add ψ𝜓\psi to the RHS to obtain Γ⊢Δ,φ→ψ,ψ\Gamma\vdash\Delta,\varphi\rightarrow\psi,\psi using the (→RI)superscriptsubscript→𝑅𝐼({\rightarrow_{R}^{I}}) rule, since by reverse persistence the current world must reject everything that some successor world rejects. Now that ψ𝜓\psi is on the RHS, we need to apply the (→R)subscript→𝑅({\rightarrow_{R}}) rule to create the φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi-successor Γ,φ⊢ψprovesΓ𝜑𝜓\Gamma,\varphi\vdash\psi only if φ𝜑\varphi is not already on the LHS. For if φ∈L​H​S𝜑𝐿𝐻𝑆\varphi\in LHS, then the successor Γ⊢ψprovesΓ𝜓\Gamma\vdash\psi that fulfills φ→ψ→𝜑𝜓\varphi\rightarrow\psi can be the current world itself. So there is no point creating it explicitly.

Corollary 5

𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} is characterised by finite rooted reflexive and transitive di-trees of reflexive points.

6 Conclusions and Future Work

Our cut-free calculus for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt} enjoys terminating backward proof-search and is sound and complete w.r.t Kripke semantics. A simple Java implementation of 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} is available at http://users.rsise.anu.edu.au/~linda. The next step is to add a cut rule to 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt}, and prove cut elimination syntactically. We are also extending our work to the modal logic 𝚂𝟻𝚂𝟻\mathtt{S5}, and the tense logic 𝙺𝚝.𝚂𝟺formulae-sequence𝙺𝚝𝚂𝟺\mathtt{Kt.S4}. Our approach of existential branching and inter-premise communication bears some similarities to hypersequents of Pottinger and Avron [1]. It would be interesting to investigate this correspondence further. From an automated deduction perspective, 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} is the first step towards an efficient decision procedure for 𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝𝙱𝚒𝙸𝚗𝚝\mathtt{BiInt}. The next task is to analyse the computational complexity of 𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭𝐆𝐁𝐢𝐈𝐧𝐭\mathbf{GBiInt} and investigate which of the traditional optimisations for tableaux systems are still applicable in the intuitionistic case.

We would like to thank the anonymous reviewers for their suggestions.
